<Rewrite PAsource="" >A COUPLE appeared in </Rewrite>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >court yesterday </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >charged with cruelty </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >after </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >a diet of junkfood </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >saw their son balloon </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >to 22 stone </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >at the age of 12. </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Richard Thomas</Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >, who is now an 18-year-old student and has slimmed to 15 stone after leaving home, </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >told a jury </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >how he was fed </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >chips </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >every day. </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >'Occasionally I ate pasty and chips or jumbo sausage with chips - but mainly it was just chips,' </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >he said.
</Rewrite>

<Verbatim PAsource="" >'I got used to it. I would wait for my parents to come back in the evening for our meal. </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >We would regularly live on chippy meals. Food was never prepared in the house ever. Most nights they would come home with a whole load of chips. </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >I weigh l5stone now but </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >I used to be 22 stone when I was 12. </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >I had to sleep on a double-bed. I was very fat then.' 
</New>

<Rewrite PAsource="" >Self-employed </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >businessman Christopher Grant, 45, </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >and his wife </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Meryl, 43, </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >who were accused of </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >failing to provide </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >their son with </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >adequate food, </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >were also said to have dressed the boy in old second-hand clothes while his step-mother had a wardrobe full of designer wear </New>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >Mr </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Thomas</Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >, who is now 5ft 10ins, </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >told Cardiff Crown Court </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >that his </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >parents </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >would hurl abuse at him for being overweight.
</Rewrite>

<Verbatim PAsource="" >'My name in the house was "stupid fat b******",' </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >he added. </New>
<New PAsource="" >'I would get up in the morning and have toast but only if my parents had bothered to buy any bread. </New>
<New PAsource="" >I wore dirty, second-hand clothes, and did all the housework or else I was beaten by my dad and then have chips for tea. </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >My father would punch me almost every day and Meryl would join in by kicking me. But I was such a fat kid I could hardly feel the kicks at all.' 
</Verbatim>

<Rewrite PAsource="" >But the case against </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >the Grants, </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >who </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >denied three </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >charges </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >of cruelty </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >between 1994 to 1997, </New>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >collapsed when </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >a witness withdrew evidence </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >due to be given In </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >court.
</Verbatim>

<Verbatim PAsource="" >Susan Ferrier, </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >prosecuting, said no </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >further evidence </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >would be offered </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >and </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >the </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Recorder of Cardiff, Michael Gibbon, QC, formally found the couple not guilty.
</Verbatim>

<Verbatim PAsource="" >The Grants </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >were not required </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >to give evidence in their defence.
</Verbatim>

<New PAsource="" >Earlier, </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Mr Thomas </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >told the jury that he was often freezing in the family's five-bedroomed home and that he had to use candles for heat and light.
</New>

<Rewrite PAsource="" >Outlining the prosecution case, Miss </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Ferrier said: 'No proper food was provided. </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Instead he was regularly fed chips over and over again from a chip shop on an almost daily basis. </Verbatim>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >The only food kept in the kitchen was bread, butter and jam. </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >One friend says that when she called round the only other thing in the kitchen was chip wrappers. </New>
<New PAsource="" >The child had no new clothes. He wore second-hand clothes which were thrown away only when they wore out. </New>
<New PAsource="" >Meryl on the other hand had a wardrobe full of designer clothes and dresses, all too small for her. </New>
<New PAsource="" >She sent all her clothes out to a laundrette and they would be sent back neatly folded.' 
</New>

<Rewrite PAsource="" >Miss </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Ferrier said: </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >'He was treated as a prisoner in his own home. </New>
<New PAsource="" >He went to school but were not allowed out to socialise. </New>
<New PAsource="" >He were required to carry out household chores and if he failed would receive violence. </New>
<New PAsource="" >He was referred to In derogatory terms, being called the ugly fat b******. </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Richard regularly suffered violence and once the father had knocked him to the floor Meryl would join in and kick him'
</Verbatim>

<Verbatim PAsource="" >The Grants, </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >of The Old Coach House, </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Sully, </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >In the Vale of Glamorgan, </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >South Wales, </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >refused </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >to comment as they left the court.</Verbatim>



